@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation is a program that allows the Amiga to interface with a Heath
ID-5001 Advanced Weather Computer.

The ID-5001 is a sophisticated digital weather monitor, capable of
displaying a wide variety of weather readings, including temperature
(indoor and outdoor), barometric pressure, wind speed and direction,
humidity (indoor and outdoor), and rainfall. In addition it keeps track of
the rate of change of the values it monitors, and it remembers the highest
and lowest readings and the time and date when they occurred.

Beyond making all of this data available via its front panel LCD, the
ID-5001 also features a serial port, allowing all of its data to be
accessed remotely. That's where WeatherStation comes in. It allows the
Amiga to connect to the ID-5001's serial port, making all of the data
available at the Amiga.

Besides being able to display all of the ID-5001's current readings, rates
of change, and weather extremes in windows on the Amiga, WeatherStation
also allows the data to be recorded and later played back in a chart
recorder-like graphical format. This capability extends the usefulness of
the ID-5001 by allowing the weather data to be stored and analyzed in more
detail.

WeatherStation features:

- @{i}Provides access to all ID-5001 data on the Amiga.@{ui}
  Monitor weather readings while word processing or surfing the Web!

- @{i}All high and low readings in one window.@{ui}
  See all of the highs and lows at once. Clear them individually, or
  all together. Option to automatically clear them all at midnight.

- @{i}Audio alert and warning annunciators.@{ui}
  Play an IFF sound whenever an alert or warning condition develops.

- @{i}Pictorial weather forecast, based on the current weather data.@{ui}
  Mostly useless, but fun to watch.

- @{i}Record weather data for further analysis.@{ui}
  Chart the data later within WeatherStation, or import it into a
  spreadsheet for additional processing. Can automatically begin recording
  at startup.

- @{i}Display weather data in a chart recorder format.@{ui}
  Graphical display format makes it easy to observe weather trends- watch
  the readings change as a front passes! Open multiple chart windows, to
  compare recordings.

- @{i}Adaptable user interface.@{ui}
  Opens on the Workbench, public screens, or its own custom screen.
  Selectable fonts and colors. Compatible with graphics cards.

- @{i}Flexible serial support.@{ui}
  Communicates via the standard Amiga serial port, or via add-on serial
  cards.

- @{i}Fully configurable.@{ui}
  Preferences settings allow WeatherStation to be set up the way you like.
  Preferences can be saved and loaded.

- @{i}Efficient, low-overhead design.@{ui}
  Runs quietly in the background, displaying or recording weather data
  without affecting foreground programs. Runs well on low-end systems.

- @{i}ARexx port.@{ui}
  Access the current weather readings from other programs.

If you don't have an ID-5001, but do have OS 3.0 or better and a JPEG
datatype, @{"here" link "ID-5001.jpg/MAIN"} is a picture of one.

@endnode

@node "Copyright" "Copyright and Distribution"

@{b}@{fg shine}Copyright@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation is copyrighted, freely redistributable software (copyright ©
1999, 2002 by Mike Steed). It is not public domain. No fee is required for
use of WeatherStation, and neither should any fee be charged for its
distribution, beyond nominal copying, media, and/or connect fees.

The intention is that if I'm not making any money from this program despite
having taken years to write it, no one else should make money merely for
passing it around.


@{b}@{fg shine}Warranty@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------@{ub}@{fg text}

While WeatherStation has been extensively tested and is believed to have no
major bugs, it is distributed without warranty. Use it at your own risk.


@{b}@{fg shine}Third Party Components@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation uses reqtools.library, copyright © 1991-1997 by Nico
François and Magnus Holmgren.

WeatherStation uses textfield.gadget, copyright © 1995 by Mark Thomas.

WeatherStation uses the Boopsi Button Class linkable library v. 37.3, by
Douglas Keller (modified to v. 37.4 by Mike Steed).

WeatherStation's GUI was designed using GadToolsBox, copyright © 1991-1993
by Jan van den Baard.

WeatherStation's ARexx port was built with ARexxBox, copyright © 1992-1993
by Michael Balzer.

This file was created with the assistance of Heddley, copyright © 1994 by
Edd Dumbill.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation is obviously intended for use with an ID-5001. It will run
without one, however, for evaluation purposes, or to examine logged data
recorded by a different Amiga.

For kit-built ID-5001s the serial port was optional. Of course,
WeatherStation will not work with an ID-5001 unless the serial port is
present. The humidity and rain sensors are also optional, but
WeatherStation will run fine without these.

WeatherStation has the following Amiga system requirements:

 - Amiga OS 2.04 or higher.
 - reqtools.library version 38 or higher (included).
 - textfield.gadget version 3 or higher (included).

WeatherStation was designed to be stingy with system resources, so it needs
relatively little memory, and doesn't use much processor power. This allows
it to run in the background, reading and displaying data from the ID-5001,
without much impact on the foreground operation of even a low-powered
Amiga.

WeatherStation was also designed to be system-legal, and so should work
well with hardware and software add-ons as long as they accurately emulate
the standard Amiga equipment (I particularly recommend MagicMenu and
CycleToMenu for use with WeatherStation).

WeatherStation has been tested with add-on serial cards (MultiFace III) and
graphics cards (Picasso II). It was tested on an Amiga 1000 running OS 2.1,
on an Amiga 3000-040 running OS 2.1 and 3.1, and on an Amiga 3000-060
running OS 3.1 and 3.9.


@{b}@{fg shine}Installation@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------@{ub}@{fg text}

Installation of WeatherStation is simple- just drag the WeatherStation
drawer to its desired location. The required files reqtools.library and
textfield.gadget are located in the drawer, and will be found by
WeatherStation when it is run.

If you already have one or more of these libraries installed, you may
delete these files from the drawer. Or, if you don't already have these
libraries installed, you may want to move reqtools.library to LIBS: and
textfield.gadget to SYS:Classes/Gadgets (under OS 3.0 or above), so that
other programs may use them as well.

WeatherStation comes with OS 3.5-style "Glow Icons." These icons include
planar images, so they will also work with OS 3.1 and older. Old-style
icons may be found in the OldIcons drawer, in case you prefer their smaller
size (both in file size and image size).

You'll need a serial cable to connect the Amiga to the ID-5001. The ID-5001
is designed to connect to a computer, so a straight through cable will work
(no null-modem is required). The connections will vary with the type of
serial port on the Amiga (9 pin vs. 25 pin). When using the standard Amiga
serial port, the following connections work for me:

                     Amiga    ID-5001
                     -----    -------
                     Pin 2 --- Pin 2
                     Pin 3 --- Pin 3
                     Pin 4 --- Pin 4
                     Pin 6 --- Pin 6
                     Pin 7 --- Pin 7
              (Other pins may be connected as
               well, but they are not required)

RS-232 is not designed to travel great distances. I've had no problems
communicating across a room at 9600 bps using a 25 foot, unshielded cable.
With a high quality, shielded cable you may be able to go even farther.
Using a slower baud rate may be helpful with very long cables.

In theory WeatherStation could be used to communicate remotely with an
ID-5001 via modems at both machines. I haven't tried this, and
WeatherStation does not have a dialer or any special serial handling for a
modem.

@endnode

@node "Running" "Running WeatherStation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Running WeatherStation@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation can be run from the Workbench or from the shell. To run it
from the Workbench, double-click its icon. To run it from the shell, type
"Run WeatherStation".

When WeatherStation starts up it looks for a file called
WeatherStation.prefs, in the same drawer as the program. If it finds
this file, it will use the preferences settings contained therein. If
WeatherStation.prefs can't be found, the program will use default
preferences settings.

WeatherStation attempts to read data from the ID-5001 as soon as it begins
running. If it is unable to connect with the ID-5001, it will display a
requester warning of this, and the various data displays will remain blank.
Most of the WeatherStation windows are of little use if there is no
ID-5001, but the @{"chart recorder windows" link "Chart" 0} may still be used to view recorded
weather data, and the @{"Preferences window" link "Preferences" 0} may be used to configure the
program.

You may run more than one copy of WeatherStation at a time, though on most
systems this will not be very useful, as most users only have a single
ID-5001 to talk to. If set to use different serial ports, however,
different copies of WeatherStation may be used to monitor more than one
ID-5001. Only one of these copies of WeatherStation may be running on a
custom screen, because all copies of WeatherStation use the same public
screen name. You can work around this if necessary by having the second
copy of WeatherStation open on the first copy's public screen.

@{u}Startup Options@{uu}

When first run, WeatherStation can be told to load WeatherStation data
files and open chart recorder windows to display them, and/or to begin
recording a WeatherStation data file.

There are several ways to tell WeatherStation to load and display data
files on startup. From the Workbench, you can hold down the shift key and
click up to four WeatherStation data files. While still holding the shift
key, double-click the program's icon, and it will load and display the data
files. WeatherStation can also be set as the default tool in a data file's
icon. Double-clicking the icon will run the program and it will load and
display the file.

From the shell, a list of up to four data files to display can be given
following the program name: "Run WeatherStation Filename1 Filename2
Filename3 Filename4". Standard AmigaDOS wildcards may be used for any of
the filenames. The special filename "Realtime" will cause the realtime
chart window to be opened, and may be used in addition to the standard four
filenames.

WeatherStation can also be told to begin recording a data file as soon as
it is run. From the Workbench, set the tooltype "RECORD=Filename" in the
program's icon. From the shell, add the argument "RECORD=Filename"
following the program's name (optionally with a list of files to be loaded
and displayed). The recording parameters (recording interval, etc.) will be
those saved in WeatherStation.prefs. If 'Filename' is an existing data file
it will be appended to. If it is not a WeatherStation data file, recording
will be aborted.

@{u}ID-5001 Settings@{uu}

When it starts up, WeatherStation initializes the serial port of the
ID-5001 for proper communication with itself. If you have set the ID-5001's
serial port for use with other programs, this may affect those settings.
Also, if WeatherStation is not able to communicate with the ID-5001
immediately after startup, these settings may not be made, causing problems
when the connection is later made. In this latter case, just quit and
restart WeatherStation.

The ID-5001 settings that WeatherStation requires (and sets) are:

 - No echo of incoming commands.
 - No automatic linefeed after carriage return.
 - No automatic transmit of changing readings.
 - No time alarm.
 - The time separator is a colon.
 - The date separator is a forward slash.

@endnode

@node "Windows" "WeatherStation's Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}WeatherStation's Windows@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The user interacts with WeatherStation via a number of independent windows.
Each window may be zoomed between full size, and a small "title bar only"
size. Each size of the window may have a different location. This allows
the windows to be quickly switched between full size, and a small "out of
the way" size. If even the "out of the way" size is too big, the windows
(except for the Display window)  may be closed when not in use.

@{"Display Window" link "Display" 0}

The Display window is WeatherStation's main window. It is opened when the
program is started, and closing it quits the program. It shows most of the
data available from the ID-5001's front panel, and also allows any of the
other WeatherStation windows to be opened.

@{"Hi/Lo Window" link "Hi-Lo" 0}

The Hi/Lo window makes available the high and low readings stored in the
ID-5001. It allows the readings to be cleared, individually or together.

@{"Record Control Window" link "Record Ctrl" 0}

The Record Control window is used to control WeatherStation's data
recorder. It allows recording of the current readings to be started or
stopped, and it adjusts the parameters of the recording.

@{"Chart Control Window" link "Chart Ctrl" 0}

The Chart Control window allows control over WeatherStation's chart
recorder feature. It allows up to five chart recorder windows to be opened
-- four showing prerecorded data and the fifth live data -- and it allows
the charting parameters to be set.

@{"Preferences Window" link "Preferences" 0}

The Preferences window allows WeatherStation to be configured the way you
like it. It has four pages that allow most of WeatherStation's settings to
be adjusted, saved, and reloaded.

@endnode

@node "Display" "Display Window"
@toc "Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Display Window@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The Display window duplicates, at least functionally, most of the front
panel display of the ID-5001. It is laid out similar to the ID-5001, so the
arrangement will be familiar. The window is relatively small, so it may be
kept in the corner of a screen for monitoring purposes, without obscuring
too much of the background.

The Display window contains the following readouts and controls:

@{u}Display Mode@{uu}

 These three radio buttons, located in the lower left corner of the window,
 control which values are displayed.

 @{i}Current@{ui} causes the current weather readings to be displayed. The arrows
 alongside each reading (except the wind speed) indicate the direction and
 rate of change of the reading. This corresponds to the default display for
 the ID-5001.

 @{i}Rates@{ui} causes the current (hourly) rates of change to be displayed. The
 arrows reflect this rate of change, as they do in the Current mode. This
 display corresponds to the ID-5001 display when the RATE key is being
 pressed. Except: The rainfall rate is the instantaneous rain rate, based
 on the time between the last two pulses from the rain gauge (equivalent to
 pressing RAIN and RATE on the ID-5001).

 @{i}24 Hours@{ui} causes the difference between the current readings and the
 readings 24 hours ago to be displayed. This display corresponds to the
 ID-5001 display when the 24 HOUR key is being pressed. Unlike the ID-5001,
 the arrows also reflect this 24 hour rate of change. The rainfall rate is
 not the 24 hour rate, but is rather the change over the last hour
 (equivalent to pressing the RATE key on the ID-5001).

@{u}Wind Speed and Direction@{uu}

 The wind direction is indicated by a compass rose, just like the ID-5001.
 The display has a resolution of 36 points, compared to 32 points for the
 ID-5001. The windspeed is indicated in either kph, mph, or knots. A cycle
 gadget allows the wind speed and direction to be either instantaneous (G,
 for Gust) or averaged over the last minute (A, for Average).

 The wind display is blanked when rates are being displayed, as the ID-5001
 does not measure wind rates.

@{u}Time and Date@{uu}

 The time, date, and day of week as read from the ID-5001, not the Amiga's
 internal clock. Most of the time the ID-5001's AC-line-paced clock will be
 more accurate and stable than the Amiga's crystal-paced clock.

@{u}Temperature@{uu}

 The indoor temperature is on the left and the outdoor temperature is on
 the right, just like the ID-5001. The temperature may be displayed in
 degrees C, or degrees F. The outdoor temperature is accompanied by a cycle
 gadget that allows the outdoor temperature display (T for Temperature) to
 be replaced by the outdoor wind chill temperature (C for Chill). The wind
 chill is based on either the gust wind speed, or the average wind speed,
 depending on which is currently being displayed.

@{u}Barometer@{uu}

 The current barometric pressure, in either millibars or inches.

@{u}Weather Forecast@{uu}

 A simple pictorial @{"forecast" link "Forecast" 0} of the weather conditions in about 12 hours,
 based on the current readings and rates of change. This forecast may be a
 little more accurate than that on a mechanical barometer, but not much.
 Consider it "just for fun", more than something to plan your weekend by.
 The forecast may be disabled if you don't find it entertaining.

@{u}Humidity@{uu}

 The indoor humidity is on the left and the outdoor humidity is on the
 right, just like the ID-5001. The humidity is displayed in percent. If you
 don't have humidity sensors on your ID-5001 then these displays will be
 blank.

@{u}Fog@{uu}

 The display box to the right of the outdoor humidity will display the
 legend "Fog" when the ID-5001 determines that fog is possible.

@{u}Rainfall@{uu}

 The current rainfall, in centimeters or inches. Unlike the ID-5001,
 WeatherStation has a rate arrow for the rainfall. If you don't have a rain
 gauge on your ID-5001 then this display will be blank.

@{u}Alert/Warning@{uu}

 The display box to the right of the rainfall will display the legend
 "Alert" or the legend "Warning" when the rates of change exceed certain
 thresholds. Depending on a preferences setting, these thresholds may be
 taken from the ID-5001, or they may be calculated independently by
 WeatherStation. WeatherStation may be configured to sound an audio alarm
 when an alert or a warning condition is present.

@{u}Window Callups@{uu}

 There are four buttons, corresponding to the four other WeatherStation
 windows. Pressing a button will open the corresponding window. If the
 window is already open, it will be zoomed to full size and brought to the
 front.

The Display window contains the following menus:

@{u}Project@{uu}

 @{i}About@{ui} brings up the "about" requester, which has credits for the program,
 and displays the version number and date of the program.

 @{i}Quit@{ui} quits the program. If weather data is being recorded, you will be
 asked to confirm that you really want to quit. If any other programs have
 opened windows on WeatherStation's public screen, it will wait for them to
 be closed before quitting.

@{u}Windows@{uu}

 The four choices in this menu correspond to the four other WeatherStation
 windows. Selecting one of these menu items will open the corresponding
 window. If the window is already open, it will be zoomed to full size and
 brought to the front.

@endnode

@node "Hi-Lo" "Hi/Lo Window"
@toc "Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Hi/Lo Window@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The Hi/Lo window provides access to all of the ID-5001's high and low
readings at once, along with the time and date at which they occurred. The
readings are real-time, and will update if any new high or low readings are
recorded. Because it takes time to read all of the highs and lows from the
ID-5001, the @{"Display window" link "Display" 0} will update more slowly when this window is
open (only significant when the update interval is set to Continuous).

In addition, the Hi/Lo window contains the following controls:

@{u}Clear Buttons@{uu}

 Each high and low reading is accompanied by a clear button. Pressing the
 button will clear only that reading. The reading is cleared immediately;
 there is no confirmation requester.

@{u}Clear All@{uu}

 This button will cause all of the high and low readings to be cleared. A
 warning requester will appear first, to ask for confirmation. The rainfall
 is not cleared by this button.

@{u}Clear Rain@{uu}

 This button will zero the rainfall. The rainfall is cleared immediately;
 there is no confirmation requester. Rainfall is cleared separately from
 the other readings because some users may prefer to track the rainfall on
 a per-storm or even a per-season basis, rather than daily.

@{u}Auto Clear at Midnight@{uu}

 If selected, this checkbox will cause all of the readings (except the
 rainfall) to be automatically cleared immediately after midnight. This is
 useful when tracking highs and lows on a daily basis. The readings are not
 saved before being cleared, so be sure to record them first if you want to
 preserve them.

The Hi/Lo window contains the following menu:

@{u}Hi/Lo Window@{uu}

 @{i}Close@{ui} closes the window. WeatherStation will stop monitoring the high and
 low readings, allowing the Display window readings to update faster.

@endnode

@node "Record Ctrl" "Record Control Window"
@toc "Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Record Control Window@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The Record Control window controls WeatherStation's weather data recorder.
This window allows you to record a series of weather readings at regular
intervals, for later playback by the @{"chart recorder" link "Chart Ctrl" 0}, or for import into
another program for more detailed analysis.

The Record Control window contains the following controls:

@{u}Readings To Record@{uu}

This series of checkboxes controls which of the available readings will be
recorded. Disabling recording of unwanted or unavailable readings helps
reduce the size of the data file.

@{u}Record Wind Gust@{uu}
@{u}Record Wind Average@{uu}
@{u}Record Wind Chill@{uu}

 Most weather readings change relatively slowly, so that little information
 is lost in recording the reading once every few minutes or more. That's
 not true of wind-related readings, however. Because of the gusty nature of
 wind, you can easily get an inaccurate record of the peak wind speeds.
 This group of controls tells WeatherStation to keep track of the highest
 wind speed (or the lowest wind chill) during the interval between
 recordings, and to record that extreme instead of the current reading.

 If Current is selected, the current reading at the time of the recording
 will be recorded. If Highest/Lowest is selected, the most extreme reading
 during the interval since the last recording will be recorded.

@{u}Wind Units@{uu}

 The wind speed may be recorded in kilometers per hour, miles per hour, or
 knots. These units are independent of those in the Display window, and
 those in use by the ID-5001.

@{u}Temperature Units@{uu}

 The temperature may be recorded in degrees Celsius or degrees Fahrenheit.
 These units are independent of those in the Display window, and those in
 use by the ID-5001.

@{u}Barometer Units@{uu}

 The barometer may be recorded in millibars or inches. These units are
 independent of those in the Display window, and those in use by the
 ID-5001.

@{u}Rain Units@{uu}

 The rainfall may be recorded in centimeters or inches. These units are
 independent of those in the Display window, and those in use by the
 ID-5001.

@{u}Recording Interval@{uu}

 This cycle gadget selects the recording interval, one of several values
 between one minute and 15 minutes.

@{u}Recording Status@{uu}

 The display box below the Readings To Record checkboxes shows the current
 recording status. It reads "Not Recording" when recording is inactive.
 When recording is in progress, the status reads "Recording", followed by
 the size of the data file. When recording is stopped, the status will read
 "Recording Stopped".

@{u}Data File Name@{uu}

 This text gadget holds the name (and optionally the path) of the file to
 be recorded. The file button to the right brings up a file requester that
 may also be used to select a file to be recorded. It is suggested that
 WeatherStation data files be given names with a '.wxd' suffix, but this is
 not required.

@{u}Record@{uu}

 Begins recording. WeatherStation will verify the file name before writing
 to it, and will warn if the file already exists. If the name is that of an
 existing WeatherStation data file, a requester allows the choice of
 overwriting the old data, or appending to it.

 If a file named "def_WXD.info" is present in the same directory as the
 WeatherStation program, it will be used as a template to create an icon
 for the file being recorded. If the file being recorded already has an
 icon, it will not be touched.

 Most of the controls in the window are disabled while recording is in
 progress, to prevent changes that might upset the recording. The Record
 Control window may be closed while recording; doing so will not affect the
 recording. If an attempt is made to quit WeatherStation while recording,
 you will be asked to confirm that you really want to quit.

@{u}Note@{uu}

 Brings up a @{"notepad window" link "Notepad" 0}, which allows a small text note to be added to
 a weather data file being recorded. If a note is created before recording
 is started, it will be placed at the start of the data file when recording
 is later commenced. This is useful in documenting the purpose of the
 recording. If a note is created while recording is in progress, it will be
 written to the data file when the next set of readings is recorded. This
 is useful in documenting something of interest that happens while
 recording.

 If the Note button is pressed again before a newly-entered note has been
 written to the data file, the note will be redisplayed and may be further
 edited. Once the note has been written, it is erased so that a new note
 may be created. Pressing the notepad's Cancel button (or the close gadget)
 erases the note, preventing it from being recorded. This is true even when
 editing an existing note, so be careful.

@{u}Stop@{uu}

 Stops recording, and reenables the recording controls.

The Record Control window contains the following menus:

@{u}Record Window@{uu}

 @{i}Record@{ui} begins recording, just as if the Record button was pressed.

 @{i}Stop@{ui} stops recording, just as if the Stop button was pressed.

 @{i}Close@{ui} closes the window. Recording is not affected.

@endnode

@node "Chart Ctrl" "Chart Control Window"
@toc "Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Chart Control Window@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The Chart Control window controls WeatherStation's chart recorder feature.
This window allows control over the data source and chart parameters for up
to five @{"chart recorder windows" link "Chart" 0}. One of these windows charts real time
data coming from the ID-5001, while the other four chart data from
WeatherStation data files.

The Chart Control window contains the following controls:

@{u}Readings To Chart@{uu}

 This series of checkboxes controls which of the available readings will be
 charted. Readings that were not recorded, or that are not available from
 the ID-5001, may not be charted.

@{u}Wind Units@{uu}

 The wind speed may be charted in kilometers per hour, miles per hour, or
 knots. The units being charted need not be the same as those that were
 recorded.

@{u}Temperature Units@{uu}

 The temperature may be charted in degrees Celsius or degrees Fahrenheit.
 The units being charted need not be the same as those that were recorded.

@{u}Barometer Units@{uu}

 The barometer may be charted in millibars or inches. The units being
 charted need not be the same as those that were recorded.

@{u}Rain Units@{uu}

 The rainfall may be charted in centimeters or inches. The units being
 charted need not be the same as those that were recorded.

@{u}Data Source@{uu}

 This cycle gadget selects which of the five chart sources is being
 controlled by the rest of the gadgets in the Chart Control window. File #1
 through File #4 are the four chart recorder windows that utilize data
 files as their input. Realtime is the chart recorder window that utilizes
 live data from the ID-5001 as its input.

@{u}Chart File Name@{uu}

 This text gadget holds the name (and optionally the path) of the data file
 that is to be charted. The file button to the right brings up a file
 requester that may also be used to select the file to be charted. These
 gadgets are disabled when the source is Realtime.

 When a file name is entered, WeatherStation scans the file (this may take
 a while for large data files). It will alert you if the file is not a
 WeatherStation data file. If the file is a data file, it will be examined
 and the Readings To Chart and Units gadgets will be updated to match the
 file contents. These automatic selections may be overridden if desired.

 WeatherStation retains a read-only lock on the selected file as long as
 its name is present here, even if it is not currently being charted. This
 will prevent the file from being deleted or edited by other programs. To
 make WeatherStation unlock the file, delete its name from this gadget.

@{u}Chart@{uu}

 Loads the data file into memory (this may take a while for large data
 files), then opens a Chart Recorder window to display the data. If the
 data file is found to have errors the load is aborted, and the chart will
 not open.

@{u}Stop@{uu}

 Closes the Chart Recorder window, and unloads the chart data from memory.
 The close gadget on the chart window will have the same effect.

The Chart Control window contains the following menus:

@{u}Chart Window@{uu}

 @{i}Source@{ui} selects the next chart data source.

 @{i}Chart@{ui} opens the chart window, just as if the Chart button was pressed.

 @{i}Stop@{ui} closes the chart window, just as if the Stop button was pressed.

 @{i}Close@{ui} closes the Chart Control window. Any chart windows that are open
 will remain open.

@endnode

@node "Preferences" "Preferences Window"
@toc "Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Preferences Window@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The Preferences window contains most of the controls that allow
WeatherStation to be configured the way you want. Note that there are no
Use or Cancel buttons in the Preferences window- most all of the
WeatherStation preferences settings are immediate, and will take place as
soon as the control is changed.

Because there are too many controls to appear in a single window, the
Preferences window is broken into four "pages", each of which contains a
subset of the controls. The cycle gadget near the lower left of the window
controls which of the four pages is displayed.

The @{"Display page" link "DisplayPrefs" 0} controls the WeatherStation Display window. It allows
setting of the display units, and controls how the rate of change arrows
respond to the changing of the weather readings.

The @{"Alert/Warn page" link "AlertWarnPrefs" 0} allows the alert and warning thresholds to be
adjusted, and controls what action is taken when an alert or a warning
occurs.

The @{"Serial page" link "SerialPrefs" 0} allows WeatherStation's serial port settings to be
adjusted to allow it to communicate with the ID-5001. The rate at which the
ID-5001 is polled is also controlled here.

The @{"Screen/Misc page" link "ScreenMiscPrefs" 0} is where you can select the screen upon which
WeatherStation will open, and which fonts and colors it will use.
Miscellaneous settings such as the program priority are also adjusted here.

In addition to the controls on the various pages, the Preferences window
contains the following controls which are present on all pages:

@{u}Load@{uu}

 Prompts you for the name of a WeatherStation preferences file, which it
 will then load and use to adjust the program's settings. If the selected
 file is not a WeatherStation preferences file, it will be ignored.

@{u}Save@{uu}

 Prompts you for a name under which to save the current WeatherStation
 preferences. This file may later be loaded in order to restore the saved
 settings.

 When first started, WeatherStation will attempt to load its initial
 settings from a file called WeatherStation.prefs, located in the same
 directory as the program. To affect the startup settings, save a
 preferences file with this name. If WeatherStation.prefs can't be found at
 startup, built-in default settings will be used.

The Preferences window contains the following menus, which are the same for
all pages:

@{u}Prefs Window@{uu}

 @{i}Page@{ui} cycles among the preferences pages.

 @{i}Load@{ui} brings up a requester to allow new preferences to be loaded, just as
 if the Load button was pressed.

 @{i}Save@{ui} brings up a requester to allow the current preferences to be saved,
 just as if the Save button was pressed.

 @{i}Close@{ui} closes the window.

Besides the settings controlled directly by the Preferences window, some
other WeatherStation settings are also stored as part of the preferences
file, and will also be loaded and saved:

- The location of WeatherStation's windows (except for the chart recorder
  windows), in both zoomed and unzoomed states.

- The "Auto Clear at Midnight" setting.

- The default @{"Record Control" link "Record Ctrl" 0} settings (units, which readings to record,
  maximum vs. current wind recording, recording interval).

- The default @{"Chart Control" link "Chart Ctrl" 0} settings (units, which readings to chart).

@endnode

@node "DisplayPrefs" "Display Preferences"
@toc "Preferences"

@{b}@{fg shine}Display Preferences@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

This page of the Preferences window contains the following controls:

@{u}Rate Settings For@{uu}

 The ID-5001 provides no way to read the rate of change arrow thresholds
 via the serial port, so these settings must be duplicated within
 WeatherStation. The thresholds may be different than those used by the
 ID-5001, if desired.

 This cycle gadget selects which weather reading the four rate arrow
 settings gadgets (below) will affect. WeatherStation supports all of the
 rate arrows that the ID-5001 does, plus a rate arrow for the rainfall
 rate.

@{u}Max. Rate@{uu}
@{u}3/4 Rate@{uu}
@{u}1/2 Rate@{uu}
@{u}Min. Rate@{uu}

 These four text boxes set the rate of change threshold at which each
 segment of the rate arrow appears. Like the ID-5001, the values here are
 independent of the display units (that is, a temperature setting of 10
 will be 10 degrees C or 10 degrees F, depending on which units are being
 displayed by WeatherStation).

 WeatherStation will warn if the thresholds are not in descending order,
 but it will use the settings anyway, with incorrect results.

@{u}Wind Units@{uu}

 The wind speed may be displayed in kilometers per hour, miles per hour, or
 knots. The units being displayed need not be the same as those that are
 being displayed by the ID-5001.

@{u}Barometer Units@{uu}

 The barometer may be displayed in millibars or inches. The units being
 displayed need not be the same as those that are being displayed by the
 ID-5001.

@{u}Temperature Units@{uu}

 The temperature may be displayed in degrees Celsius or degrees Fahrenheit.
 The units being displayed need not be the same as those that are being
 displayed by the ID-5001.

@{u}Rain Units@{uu}

 The rainfall may be displayed in centimeters or inches. The units being
 displayed need not be the same as those that are being displayed by the
 ID-5001.

@endnode

@node "AlertWarnPrefs" "Alert/Warning Preferences"
@toc "Preferences"

@{b}@{fg shine}Alert/Warning Preferences@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

This page of the Preferences window contains the following controls:

@{u}Thresholds For@{uu}

 This cycle gadget selects which weather reading the alert and warning
 threshold gadgets (below) reference. WeatherStation will generate alerts
 and warnings for all of the weather readings that the ID-5001 monitors,
 plus the rainfall.

@{u}Alert Threshold@{uu}
@{u}Warning Threshold@{uu}

 These two text boxes set the rate of change at which the alert and warning
 annunciators, respectively, activate. Like the ID-5001, the values here
 are independent of the display units (that is, a temperature setting of 10
 will be 10 degrees C or 10 degrees F, depending on which units are being
 displayed by WeatherStation).

 Like the ID-5001, the wind settings are the actual wind speeds, not the
 rates. WeatherStation will warn if the alert threshold is higher than the
 warning threshold, but it will use the settings anyway, with incorrect
 results.

@{u}Calculate Locally@{uu}

 This checkbox determines whether WeatherStation uses the alert and warning
 thresholds set with the above gadgets, or uses the thresholds of the
 ID-5001. If the box is checked, WeatherStation's thresholds (which may be
 different than those in use by the ID-5001) are used. If the box is
 unchecked, the ID-5001 thresholds are used, and the above gadgets are
 disabled. Since the ID-5001 does not generate alerts or warnings for the
 rainfall rate, this feature is not available when not calculating locally.

@{u}Alert Action@{uu}
@{u}Warning Action@{uu}

 These two cycle gadgets determine what action WeatherStation takes when
 one of the alert or warning thresholds is exceeded. Do Nothing means that
 WeatherStation will do nothing beyond illuminating the alert or warning
 annunciator. Flash Screens will cause WeatherStation to visually flash all
 of the Amiga's screens, which can optionally play a sound under OS 2.1 and
 above. Play Sound will cause WeatherStation to play an IFF sound.

@{u}Alert Sound Name@{uu}
@{u}Warning Sound Name@{uu}

 These text gadgets hold the names (and optionally the paths) of the sound
 files that WeatherStation will play when an alert or a warning,
 respectively, occurs. The file buttons to the right bring up a file
 requester that may also be used to select the sound files.

 When a file name is entered, WeatherStation loads and plays the sound as a
 test, and so you can hear what it sounds like. WeatherStation will alert
 you if the file is not an IFF 8SVX sound.

 WeatherStation does not perform double-buffering of sound files, so it
 will not play sounds longer than 128K bytes per channel (longer sounds
 will be truncated). Nor does it play more than the first octave of a
 multi-octave instrument. It does handle compressed sounds and stereo
 sounds.

@endnode

@node "SerialPrefs" "Serial Preferences"
@toc "Preferences"

@{b}@{fg shine}Serial Preferences@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

This page of the Preferences window contains the following controls:

@{u}Display Update Interval@{uu}

 This cycle gadget selects the interval at which WeatherStation reads the
 weather data from the ID-5001. This in turn affects the rate at which
 WeatherStation updates the Display and Hi/Lo windows. (The recording and
 realtime chart windows are unaffected by this setting.)

 The available update intervals vary, depending on the baud rate in use.
 Intervals of 60 and 30 seconds are available at all baud rates. Intervals
 of 20, ten, and five seconds are available at 2400 baud and above. A two
 second interval is available only at 9600 baud.

 Available at all baud rates is the setting Continuous. This causes
 WeatherStation to read from the ID-5001 as fast as possible, given the
 current baud rate and the amount of data that must be read. At 9600 baud,
 with the Hi/Lo window closed, the Display window will be updated roughly
 twice per second.

 WeatherStation has been designed to be very efficient when updating its
 windows, so that the Continuous setting may be used without unduly
 affecting other programs.

@{u}Serial Device Name@{uu}

 This text gadget allows the name of the serial device to be set, allowing
 WeatherStation to be used with add-on serial ports. The file button to the
 right brings up a file requester that may also be used to select the
 serial device. (Note that some serial.device replacements, such as the
 MultiFace duart.device, will not show up in the file requester. In this
 case the name must be typed in.) It's not a good idea to select a device
 that isn't really a serial device.

@{u}Serial Device Unit@{uu}

 This text gadget accepts the number of the serial device unit to use.
 Usually this is zero, but it may be otherwise if a multi-port serial card
 is being used. The card's documentation should indicate which unit
 corresponds to which port.

@{u}Serial Data Rate@{uu}

 This cycle gadget tells WeatherStation to use one of three common baud
 rates for communication with the ID-5001. The rate selected here must
 match the serial port rate of the ID-5001. 9600 bps is the fastest rate
 supported by the ID-5001, and is the rate of choice. There is usually
 little need to use the slower baud rates (2400 bps and 300 bps), but they
 might be useful in reducing the processor load on a low-end Amiga, or when
 using a very long serial cable.

@{u}Use Settings@{uu}

 Unlike most WeatherStation preferences settings, the serial port settings
 do not take effect as soon as they are made. Instead, pressing this button
 closes the serial port and reopens it with the new settings. This allows
 the serial port changes to take effect all at once, instead of
 sequentially.

 On rare occasions WeatherStation may get confused and stop talking to the
 ID-5001. Pressing this button will reset the serial port and get things
 going again.

@endnode

@node "ScreenMiscPrefs" "Screen/Misc. Preferences"
@toc "Preferences"

@{b}@{fg shine}Screen/Miscellaneous Preferences@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

This page of the Preferences window contains the following controls:

@{u}Screen Selection@{uu}

 These radio buttons select the screen that WeatherStation will use to hold
 its windows.

 @{i}Workbench Screen@{ui} tells WeatherStation to open on the Workbench.

 @{i}Public Screen@{ui} tells WeatherStation to open on a public screen. A requester
 listing all of the currently available public screens will appear,
 allowing the desired screen to be chosen. Since the Workbench screen is
 public, it may be selected here as well.

 @{i}Custom Screen@{ui} tells WeatherStation to open on its own custom screen. A
 screen mode requester appears, allowing the screen mode and resolution to
 be chosen. The screen depth is always two, allowing for four colors.
 WeatherStation's screen is public (the name is WeatherStationScreen), and
 other programs may open windows on it.

 If WeatherStation is unable to open on a public screen or a custom screen,
 it will fall back to opening on the Workbench.

@{u}Select Screen@{uu}

 This button recalls the public screen or screen mode requester so that a
 different public or custom screen may be selected. It is disabled when
 WeatherStation is running on the Workbench.

@{u}Palette@{uu}

 When WeatherStation is open on a custom screen, this button brings up a
 palette requester to allow the screen's colors to be changed. This button
 is disabled when running on the Workbench or on a public screen.

@{u}Screen Font@{uu}

 This text gadget allows the screen font to be set when WeatherStation is
 running on a custom screen. The button to the right brings up a font
 requester that may also be used to select the screen font. The font name
 is entered without the '.font' suffix, and it is followed by a space and
 then the font size. If the selected font can't be found, WeatherStation
 falls back to using Topaz 8.

 The screen font is used in the screen and window title bars, the menus,
 and most requesters. It is typically set to a relatively large and
 readable font. When running on the Workbench or on a public screen,
 WeatherStation uses that screen's font, and this gadget is disabled.

@{u}Window Font@{uu}

 This text gadget allows the window font to be set. The button to the right
 brings up a font requester that may also be used to select the window
 font. The font name is entered without the '.font' suffix, and it is
 followed by a space and then the font size. If the selected font can't be
 found, WeatherStation falls back to using Topaz 8.

 The window font is used in the interior of WeatherStation's windows. It
 will often be set to a small font, so that WeatherStation will not take up
 too much room when running on the Workbench or on another program's public
 screen.

 WeatherStation is font adaptive, and will scale its windows to fit the
 selected font and size. There are limits to this adaptability however, and
 visual incongruities can occur if the font is too large or too small.

@{u}Weather Forecast@{uu}

 This checkbox, when checked, causes the @{"weather forecast" link "Forecast" 0} to appear on the
 Display window. When cleared the forecast does not appear.

@{u}Priority@{uu}

 This text gadget allows WeatherStation's priority to be set. The allowable
 range of priorities is -9 to +9.

 Setting WeatherStation's priority to a value higher than that of most
 programs allows it to run undisturbed by those programs. A priority of 1
 or 2 works well in most situations. Because WeatherStation uses very
 little processor time, it will not significantly slow down lower priority
 programs.

@endnode

@node "Chart" "Chart Recorder Windows"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Chart Recorder Windows@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}--------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

When WeatherStation is asked to chart weather data, it does so by opening a
chart window. This window displays the weather data in a format resembling
that of a mechanical strip chart recorder, with the data appearing in
horizontal strips that may be scrolled from side to side.

The chart window is sizeable, and may be zoomed between two different sizes
and positions. The horizontal scale of the window is absolute, so that
enlarging the window allows more data to be seen. The vertical scale is
relative to the window size, so that enlarging the window expands the
chart, allowing more detail to be seen.

Depending on which readings are being charted, up to six strips may appear
in each chart window:

 @{i}Wind Speed@{ui} displays both the gust and the average wind speeds.

 @{i}Wind Direction@{ui} displays both the gust and the average wind directions.

 @{i}Temperature@{ui} displays the indoor and the outdoor temperatures, as well as
 the outdoor wind chill.

 @{i}Barometer@{ui} displays the barometer reading.

 @{i}Humidity@{ui} displays the indoor and the outdoor humidities.

 @{i}Rainfall@{ui} displays the rainfall rate, or delta. This is the difference
 between each rainfall reading and the one prior to it.

Below the chart strips is a display of the time and date at which the chart
readings were recorded. At the lower left of the window is the legend,
which identifies the colors used in each of the chart strips.

At the bottom of the window are the control gadgets:

 The + and - buttons control the horizontal scale of the chart. The +
 button magnifies the chart, while the - button reduces it.

 The scroller gadget allows the data to be scrolled left and right within
 the chart window, so that any portion of the data may be viewed.

If any text notes have been recorded with the data file, they will be
represented by event markers, dashed vertical lines running across the
chart strips. Double-clicking the mouse on an event marker will open a
window displaying the corresponding note.

The chart window contains the following menus:

@{u}Chart@{uu}

 @{i}Stop@{ui} stops charting the data and closes the window. The action is the same
 as if the Stop button on the Chart Control window was pressed. The
 window's close gadget also has the same effect.

@{u}Vertical Scale@{uu}

 The span of a chart is the difference between the value at the bottom of
 the chart and the value at the top of the chart. Changing the span changes
 the amplitude of the data. The range of a chart is the value at the center
 of the chart. Changing the range moves the data up and down.

 The span and range of each chart strip is set automatically when the chart
 is first opened. These automatic settings may be manually adjusted once
 the chart is open. The realtime data chart window performs an automatic
 adjustment of the span and range settings periodically as data is added to
 the chart, to accommodate changing readings. These automatic adjustments
 will override any manual settings that have been made.

 @{i}Wind Speed @{ui}adjusts the scale of the windspeed chart. Auto automatically
 sets the chart span based on the data being charted. Span + and Span -
 increase and decrease the span of the chart. The range of the chart is
 fixed, with zero always at the bottom.

 @{i}Wind Direction@{ui} adjusts the scale of the wind direction chart. Auto
 automatically sets the chart range based on the data being charted. Range
 + and Range - toggle the range of the chart so that either North or South
 is at the center of the chart. The span of the chart is fixed at 360
 degrees.

 @{i}Temperature@{ui} adjusts the scale of the temperature chart. Auto automatically
 sets the chart span and range based on the data being charted. Span + and
 Span - increase and decrease the span of the chart. Range + and Range -
 adjust the chart range up and down.

 @{i}Barometer@{ui} adjusts the scale of the barometer chart. Auto automatically
 sets the chart span and range based on the data being charted. Span + and
 Span - increase and decrease the span of the chart. Range + and Range -
 adjust the chart range up and down.

 @{i}Humidity@{ui} adjusts the scale of the humidity chart. Auto automatically sets
 the chart span and range based on the data being charted. Span + and Span
 - increase and decrease the span of the chart. Range + and Range - adjust
 the chart range up and down.

 @{i}Rainfall@{ui} adjusts the scale of the rainfall chart. Auto automatically sets
 the chart span based on the data being charted. Span + and Span - increase
 and decrease the span of the chart. The range of the chart is fixed, with
 zero always at the bottom.

@{u}Horizontal Scale@{uu}

 Allows the horizontal scale of the chart to be set to one of five values
 between one minute per pixel and 15 minutes per pixel. When the chart is
 first opened the scale is set equal to that used when recording the data,
 such that there is one data point per pixel. This automatic scaling may be
 overridden once the chart is open.

 The recording interval for the realtime chart is fixed at once per minute,
 so this is the initial horizontal scale. The scale may be adjusted once
 the chart is open, just like the other charts.

@endnode

@node "Notepad" "The Notepad"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Notepad@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------@{ub}@{fg text}

The notepad window is used to allow the entry and display of the file notes
that WeatherStation embeds within its recorded weather data files. The
notepad window operates in one of two modes: edit mode, and display-only
mode.

When entering a file note from the @{"Record Control window" link "Record Ctrl" 0}, the notepad
window is in edit mode. Text may be typed into the window, and edited using
the keyboard, mouse, and edit menu.

A blinking vertical bar cursor marks the point at which text appears when
typed. The cursor may be moved with the arrow keys, or by clicking with the
mouse. Text may be highlighted by clicking, then dragging with the mouse.
Highlighted text may be cut or copied to the clipboard, erased, or replaced
with other text by typing. The contents of the clipboard may be pasted into
the window at the cursor, or may replace highlighted text.

The notepad window will wrap text at the right edge of the window, even if
you do not press the return key. Resizing the window will cause the wrap
points to change to match the new window size. If you want more control
over the format of the text, you may press return to force a line break.
These line breaks will remain, even when the window is resized. The @{"WXD" link "WXD File Format" 0}
@{"data file format" link "WXD File Format" 0} limits the length of a file note line to 78 characters,
so WeatherStation will force a line break if necessary to comply. In
addition, there may be no more than about 2000 characters in a single file
note.

The OK button accepts any changes made to the text, and returns it to the
Record Control window, ready to be recorded. The Cancel button (and the
window's close gadget) discards all of the text, even that which was
already present when the window was first opened. Think of the Cancel
button as cancelling the entire file note, not just the most recent edits.

When displaying a file note from a @{"chart recorder window" link "Chart" 0}, the notepad
window is in display-only mode. Text may be selected by dragging with the
mouse, and may be copied to the clipboard, but the text may not be edited.
The OK button closes the window.

When it first opens, the display window is sized to fit the length of the
lines of text it must display. The window may be resized as desired once
open, and the text will reformat to fit. It might be advantageous to use
the enter key to force the lines to be short (around 40 characters) when
entering the note, in order to keep the initial display window size
relatively small.

The notepad window makes use of Mark Thomas' textfield.gadget for its
functionality. The undo function is currently not very useful, operating
more as a "replace the last deleted text" function than as a true undo.
Perhaps a future version of the textfield.gadget will implement a better
undo. If a newer version of textfield.gadget becomes available, just copy
it over the old version and WeatherStation will automatically make use of
it.

@endnode

@node "Forecast" "Weather Forecast"

@{b}@{fg shine}Weather Forecast@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------@{ub}@{fg text}

One of WeatherStation's features is a pictorial weather forecast. This
forecast attempts to predict the weather in about 12 hours, based on the
current weather readings and rates of change.

The forecast algorithm currently in use looks at the barometric pressure
and its rate of change, and at the humidity, in determining how likely it
is to be cloudy. If it is going to be clear or partly cloudy, either a moon
or a sun icon will be displayed, depending on the time of day in 12 hours.

If it is going to be cloudy or partly cloudy, the algorithm looks at the
barometer and the rain sensor to determine how likely it is that there will
be precipitation. If precipitation is forecast, it looks at the wind chill
and the rate of temperature change to decide if the precipitation will be
rain or snow.

Finally, the forecast algorithm looks at the rate of change of the
barometer to decide whether to forecast windy conditions.

Because it takes into account a variety of readings and their rates of
change, WeatherStation's forecast is more accurate than that of a barometer
alone. It is no substitute for the National Weather Service, however. One
failing is that WeatherStation cannot see the sky. Observation of the
current sky condition can tell a lot, and lacking this information
WeatherStation tends to predict "partly cloudy" a lot. A "partly cloudy"
forecast can be interpreted as meaning "no change to the current
conditions" as well as its more literal meaning.

In an attempt to work in a variety of geographic locations,
WeatherStation's forecaster does not take the wind direction into account
when generating a forecast. I could improve the accuracy of the forecast
for my home by doing so, but this might make it less accurate for someone
else. WeatherStation ignores the time of year for the same reason.

Though it will never be astoundingly accurate, the challenge of automated
forecasting will probably keep me tweaking the forecaster in future
versions of WeatherStation. In theory it would even be possible for
WeatherStation to monitor the result of its forecasts to see whether it was
right or wrong, and to adjust them accordingly, thus "learning" about the
weather patterns in a particular location. In practice this would require
that WeatherStation run 24 hours a day, and so is probably not practical.

@endnode

@node "Recording" "Notes on Recording"

@{b}@{fg shine}Notes on Recording@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation uses a @{"custom file format" link "WXD File Format" 0} called "WXD" for recording
weather data. This file format is designed to be versatile and easy to work
with, both by WeatherStation, and by other programs.

WeatherStation allows notes to be included as part of the weather data
files. These notes may be used to indicate the purpose of the recording, or
to identify particular events that occur during the recording. The notes
will cause event markers to appear when the recording is later viewed in a
@{"chart recorder window" link "Chart" 0}. The note may be displayed by double-clicking on the
event marker.

There is no way to add a note to an existing weather data file from within
WeatherStation. However, because WXD files are simple ASCII text files, any
text editor or word processor may be used to add notes. The description of
the WXD file format spells out the form the notes should take.

When recording a weather data file, the file is kept locked with a write-
only lock as long as recording is in progress. This prevents other programs
from accessing the file and possibly preventing WeatherStation from being
able to write to it.

WeatherStation only opens a file it is recording long enough to write one
record to it. It then closes the file again until it's time to write the
next record. This is a safety measure. Should the power go out or the Amiga
crash while a file is being recorded, the fact that the file is closed
means that the disk will not be corrupted.

If an error occurs while writing to the file being recorded, the @{"Record" link "Record Ctrl" 0}
@{"Control Window" link "Record Ctrl" 0} will be opened (if closed), and a requester will appear
announcing the error.

If you put a default icon (def_WXD.info) in WeatherStation's directory, it
will use that icon for every WXD file it creates. The position, tool types,
and default tool of the new file's icon will be identical to those of the
default icon. A sample default icon is provided. To prevent the creation
of icons for WXD files, just delete or rename the default icon.

By setting the "RECORD=Filename" tooltype in WeatherStation's icon, the
program can be made to start recording automatically whenever it is run.
If 'Filename' already exists it will be appended to, allowing a single file
to continuously accumulate data whenever WeatherStation is running. If
WeatherStation is put in the WBStartup drawer it will begin recording
automatically whenever the Amiga is booted (in this case you'll want to add
the "DONOTWAIT" tooltype as well). This allows for automated data recording
that can recover following a crash or power outage.

Depending on how many readings are being recorded, and the particular
values being recorded, each record is typically 40 to 50 bytes long. There
is a small amount of overhead added by the WXD file format, and file notes
take still more space. A "typical" recording of 24 hours worth of data,
with a recording interval of five minutes, will therefore take about 12K to
13K bytes of disk space. A recording interval of 15 minutes will use about
one third as much disk space, while a recording interval of one minute will
take five times as much disk space.

The best recording interval to use depends on what use you will be making
of the recorded data (and to some extent, how much space you have to hold
it). When recording events of relatively short duration (the passage of a
front, or a thunderstorm, for example) a short recording interval may be
useful in order to be able to derive as much detail as possible, especially
when the readings are expected to change abruptly.

For most recording, an interval of five minutes is good. It makes for
smaller disk files, but because most weather readings don't change much in
only five minutes, little detail is lost. Recording the highest wind
readings, instead of the current readings, helps to avoid missing out on
peak wind speeds due to the longer recording interval.

There is no maximum size to a weather data file that is being recorded,
though the recording status display will stop counting up when the file
reaches a size of 999.9K bytes. However, the WeatherStation chart recorder
cannot read a file with more than 65,535 records. Even at one minute per
record, this is more than 45 days worth of data, and so should not be a
serious limitation.

Note that it is possible to concatenate multiple WXD files together, to
form a single larger file. The AmigaDOS JOIN command may be used to do
this, as may a text editor or word processor. This ability might be useful
to join a series of daily files together into a weekly file, for example.

When reading such a "composite" file, the WeatherStation chart recorder
will skip over small gaps in the data (four hours or less). Longer gaps
will result in the data following the gap being ignored. Keep this in mind
when joining files together, or when using the "RECORD=Filename" tooltype
to automatically record data as described above.

Also keep in mind that WeatherStation requires that all of the data
segments in a "composite" file have the same recording parameters
(recording interval, measurement units, etc.). If a data segment with
incompatible parameters is encountered when reading a data file, it and all
succeeding data segments will be ignored.

@endnode

@node "Charting" "Notes on Charting"

@{b}@{fg shine}Notes on Charting@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------------@{ub}@{fg text}

The @{"chart recorder windows" link "Chart" 0} are WeatherStation's most powerful tools for
observing the weather. They allow you to go beyond just watching the
current conditions, and to actually study how the readings change over
time, by themselves and in relation to other readings. By opening multiple
chart windows it's even possible to compare and contrast recordings made at
different times.

WeatherStation can chart weather data from two sources: @{"WXD format weather" link "WXD File Format" 0}
@{"data files" link "WXD File Format" 0} recorded earlier, and real-time data coming from the ID-5001.
Some of the capabilities of the chart windows vary with the source of the
data.

When charting a recorded data file, the available data naturally depends on
what was originally recorded. It is possible to exclude data from being
charted, in order to focus on particular readings. In particular, if there
are no readings to be charted in a particular chart strip, that strip will
not appear, allowing the remaining strips to be larger.

The horizontal scale may be varied, but the resolution of the data depends
on the original recording interval. The chart recorder can handle up to
65,535 pre-recorded readings.

Because the change in rainfall during the recording interval is what is
recorded, the rainfall amounts will appear to vary with the recording 
interval (i.e., the longer the recording interval, the larger the rainfall
amounts will be). This should be kept in mind when comparing rainfall
charts recorded at different intervals.

One difference when charting real-time data is that the data is not
recorded anywhere other than on the chart. When the chart window is closed,
the data is lost. Since the readings to be charted can only be changed when
the chart window is closed, there is no way to turn readings on and off
without losing data. Similarly, it is not possible to change the units
without losing data.

When charting realtime data, the recording interval is always one minute.
Up to 1440 readings (24 hours worth) may be charted. The realtime chart
window always records wind readings in "record highest" mode, so the
readings charted are the highest (or lowest, for the wind chill) observed
over the last minute.

If you want to watch the weather data in real time while also preserving it
for future viewing, it is possible to record the readings while
simultaneously viewing the realtime chart window.

Note that, regardless of the data source, the vertical scales displayed at
the left end of the chart do not have decimal points, in order to conserve
window space. A barometer reading of 3000 inches, for instance, actually
represents 30.00 inches. Similarly, a rainfall of 10 cm actually represents
0.10 cm.

@endnode

@node "History" "History"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Genesis of WeatherStation@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

I have always been interested in the weather, and have been keeping weather
observations and notes for 27 years. I have used a number of different
weather instruments to help me gather these observations. Being a high-tech
guy, I purchased a CompuTemp 3 digital high-low thermometer in 1984 (it's
still running, and serves as a backup to the ID-5001).

The CompuTemp was very nice for keeping track of temperature, but I began
to long for something that would allow me to monitor other weather
readings, like the wind and the barometer. Remembering that Heathkit used
to sell a digital weather monitor, I acquired a Heathkit catalog. When I
saw the new ID-5001, with its large LCD screen and RS-232 interface, I
knew I had found what I was looking for.

I bought an ID-5001 kit early in 1990. It took some time to build it, get
it accurately calibrated, and get all of the sensors installed, but by the
spring of 1990 it was up and gathering data. I soon wrote a BASIC program
for my Radio Shack Model 100, so that I could plug the M100 into the
ID-5001 while I was away on vacation, and the M100 would record the high
and low readings every day, for perusal on my return.

After using my "vacation monitor" program for several years, I began to
think about how I could monitor the weather in more detail, by recording
the readings every few minutes, then plotting the result on a graph. The
Amiga seemed perectly suited to this task. So in 1994, having completed my
work on FontView, I started planning WeatherStation.

S.I.G.H. once upon a time sold a product that ran on the Amiga and
interfaced to an ID-5001. I purposely avoided this product, as I didn't
want to be accused of "borrowing" anything. From what I saw of their
advertising, SIGH-Low was an ARexx package that ran more or less as an
interface between the ID-5001 and a spreadsheet that provided the graphing
functions. As a programmer, I wanted to create something more integrated
than that. The result, of course, was WeatherStation.

It takes a long time to write a complex program like WeatherStation when
only working a few hours at a time, after work and on weekends. During the
five years that I worked on WeatherStation 1.0, the Amiga world changed
dramatically, going through two bankruptcies, three owners, and the near
disappearance of the commercial Amiga market. Heathkit underwent changes
as well, leaving the kit market and becoming a "learn by mail" course
vendor. The ID-5001 has gone through almost as many owners as the Amiga,
and is currently sold as the Weather-Quest 5001 by Forecast Technologies
(www.webbcon.com/forecasttech).

At one time I entertained the thought of trying to sell WeatherStation,
commercially or as shareware, upon its completion. The changing market has
eliminated that possibility, as the number of people who own both Amigas
and ID-5001s is no doubt very small. So WeatherStation has evolved as a
program written primarily for my own use. I am making it freely available,
and if others find it useful too, that's good. If not, it will still be
useful to me.


@{b}@{fg shine}Revision History@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------@{ub}@{fg text}

@{u}Version 1.00  02-May-99@{uu}

 The initial release of WeatherStation.

 Posted to Aminet in May, 1999.

@{u}Version 1.10  21-Dec-02@{uu}

 A new version of WeatherStation, adding some new features and fixing
 some bugs.

 Posted to Aminet in January, 2003.

 New features added:

 - WeatherStation will use a default icon, found in the program directory,
   as a template to give icons to WXD files that it creates.

 - WeatherStation data files can be loaded and displayed when the program
   is first run, and the program can be set as the default tool in a data
   file's icon, causing it to run and display that file when the icon is
   double-clicked.

 - WeatherStation can automatically start recording a data file when run.

 - WeatherStation now has a basic @{"ARexx port" link "ARexx" 0}, allowing external programs to
   open chart windows, start and stop data recording, and read the current
   weather conditions.

 - To demonstrate the ARexx port, some @{"example ARexx scripts" link "ARexx" 28} are provided.

 - OS 3.5-style "glow icons" are provided.

 - Increased the stack size in the icons to 5000 bytes- 4096 bytes was a
   litle tight.

 - Not a new program feature, but added a @{"JPEG picture" link "ID-5001.jpg/MAIN"} of an ID-5001 to
   the distribution archive, so those without one can at least see what
   it looks like.

 Bugs fixed:

 - Closing a chart window when the Chart Control window was closed would
   cause a crash. Sorry about missing that one.

 - If the gap between two segments of a multi-segment data file was
   exactly equal to the recording interval, the program would lock up when
   it attempted to load the data file.

 - Not a bug really, but attempting to load a multi-segment data file
   where the gap between segments was less than the recording interval
   would cause the latter segment to be rejected. This could cause
   problems when using WeatherStation to automatically record data files
   at startup, if the time between shutdown and startup was short (as
   it might be following a crash or a power glitch). Reworked the code
   to handle gaps between segments more flexibly.

@endnode

@node "Author" "Author"

@{b}@{fg shine}About the Author@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------------@{ub}@{fg text}

I live and work in Santa Cruz, California, about 75 miles south of San
Francisco on the central California coast.

By profession, I am an electronic engineer and embedded systems programmer;
my work with Amigas is (alas) only as a hobby. I learned BASIC and assembly
language programming on an Apple ][+ ($2400, 1 MHz, 48K RAM, 140K floppy)
purchased in 1982.

I bought my Amiga 1000 in the spring of 1986 (with AmigaOS 1.1), and
immediately set about programming it in AmigaBASIC. I released FScapePlus,
a fractal landscape drawing program, in November of 1986. It was featured
in the Sep/Oct 1987 issue of Info magazine, along with the comment that it
"throws out the challenge for developers to come up with commercial fractal
landscape packages."

I switched to programming in Multi-Forth in 1987. In July of 1987 I
released FileView, a simple text file viewer. FileView continued to be
useful for many years, and I was pleased to note that it took advantage of
things like ECS screen resolutions and user-selectable fonts that were
introduced long after it was written. I produced a number of Multi-Forth
programming utilities in the following years. I began work on a general-
purpose charting and graphing program, but abandoned it when it became
impractical to continue using Multi-Forth.

I purchased an A3000 in 1991, and switched to programming in SAS C when
Multi-Forth was abandoned by its creators. In 1994 I released FontView, a
font display program that served as both a "learning C" exercise, and a
useful utility. Although it was written for both OS 1.3 and 2.0, and so
doesn't fully take advantage of OS 2.0+ features, FontView continues to be
useful whenever I want to check out a newly acquired font.

I'm still using my A3000 today, upgraded with a 68060, HD floppy drives, a
Picasso II graphics card, a MultiFace III I/O card, OS 3.1 ROMs, and a
CD-RW drive. It was on this system that I wrote WeatherStation, using SAS
C 6.58. I still have the A1000 as well (upgraded with a hard drive and OS
2.1), and used it to test WeatherStation on a low-end system.

I use Wintel machines at work, and despite their speed, low price, and vast
selection of software, I still prefer the simplicity and sophistication of
the Amiga platform. And despite the availability of any number of "Visual
Whatsit" development environments on the Wintel platform, the inherent
ugliness of the PC hardware/software environment keeps me happily turning
out Amiga programs.

I can be contacted via email at @{b}72207.463\@compuserve.com@{ub}. I would
appreciate hearing from anyone who finds WeatherStation useful- it's the
only way a freeware author has of knowing if anyone else is using the
efforts of their labors.

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs And Shortcomings"

@{b}@{fg shine}Bugs and Shortcomings@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

I believe in producing high-quality software, even if it is non-commercial
and largely for my own use. To this end, I've put in a lot of time testing
and debugging WeatherStation. As far as I know, there are no serious bugs
in WeatherStation. There are some minor ones, however, and there are
definitely some shortcomings and missing features. And of course, it's not
possible for me to test WeatherStation on a large variety of different
Amiga hardware and software configurations, so other users may come across
problems that I haven't.

If you find a bug in WeatherStation, or have a particular feature you'd
like to see added, feel free to @{"contact me" link "Author" 49}. I'll try to fix any serious
bugs, and I'll tackle the little ones as time permits. I can't promise to
add features on demand, but I'll at least consider it.

@{u}WeatherStation Bugs@{uu}

- Operations that lock out multi-tasking for periods of time can sometimes
  cause WeatherStation's serial routines to lock up, leading to a loss of
  communication with the ID-5001. I've pretty much eliminated this on my
  system when using the Amiga serial.device, but it still happens on
  occasion when using the MultiFace duart.device. It might also show up on
  other systems with different timing than mine. If this should happen,
  just click the "Use Settings" button on the serial preferences page. This
  resets the serial port, and restores proper operation.

- I've spent a lot of time working on the chart scrolling routines, to get
  them as fast as possible while still using only the standard Amiga
  graphics routines (important for maximum compatibility with graphics
  cards and future operating systems). Still, it is sometimes possible for
  minor visual glitches to appear (small gaps in the data, or "ghost
  images"). I've decided that I'd rather live with these than to slow the
  scrolling down. To force a redraw of the chart window without otherwise
  changing it, reselect the current horizontal scale.

- Under OS 2.x, buttons rendered by the Boopsi Button Class linkable
  library (used in the notepad window) sometimes end up with ghosted
  borders. I'm not sure whether this is a bug in OS 2.x, or in the Boopsi
  Button Class code.

- WeatherStation uses the Amiga's clock to know when to record and chart
  realtime data. Setting the clock while WeatherStation is running can
  cause these activities to malfunction. Specifically, setting the time
  back an hour, as at the end of daylight savings time, will cause
  recording and charting to stop for an hour.

- Speaking of daylight savings time, WeatherStation does not respond
  correctly when the ID-5001 automatically adjusts its clock at the start
  and end of daylight savings time. If WeatherStation is recording and/or
  doing realtime charting when the time changes, it will not not pick up
  the time change.

- In an attempt to be as efficient as possible, WeatherStation only
  updates the readings in the Display window when they have changed. On
  rare occasions it fails to see a changed reading when switching between
  the Current, Rates, and 24 Hour modes, leading to incorrect readings.
  If you suspect that a reading is incorrect, zoom the window to its
  minimum size and back to force the readings to be refreshed.

- Older versions of MagicMenu don't get along well with the
  textfield.gadget used to implement WeatherStation's notepad. The symptom
  is that attempting to use the notepad menu locks up the system for a
  short period of time. This is actually a bug in MagicMenu. The newest
  versions of MagicMenu have fixed this bug.

- The notepad filters out tab characters when pasting from the clipboard.
  This is a fault in the textfield.gadget.

- When using the original Picasso II software, the wind direction pointer
  on WeatherStation's main display window sometimes leaves behind "after
  images" of itself when the window is depth arranged. This seems to be a
  bug of the original Picasso II software, as it doesn't occur on native
  Amiga screens or with other RTG software.

- Depending on the window font in use, sometimes one of the digits in some
  of the Preferences window text gadgets will disappear. This can cause a
  two-digit value like 10 to appear as a single digit value like 1. This is
  most likely to happen with proportional fonts, and is really an Intuition
  weakness. The solution would be to make the text gadgets bigger, and I
  didn't want to do this as it would make the window larger or more
  crowded.

- WeatherStation seems to handle low-memory situations cleanly, though it's
  not practical to check out every possibility. However, reqtools.library
  and textfield.gadget, used by WeatherStation, tend to generate Enforcer
  hits in low memory situations.

@{u}WeatherStation Shortcomings@{uu}

- WeatherStation does not support printing. For most WeatherStation windows
  there isn't really anything to print. The chart recorder windows are the
  exception- it might be nice to be able to make a hardcopy of an
  interesting chart. I left this feature out because it would be a lot of
  work, and because I personally seldom want a printout.

- WeatherStation doesn't make maximum use of multi-tasking. It does fully
  multi-task with other programs, but internally it is a single task that
  only pretends to do more than one thing at a time. Something as simple as
  displaying a menu or dragging a window temporarily stops WeatherStation
  from reading, displaying, and recording data. This was an early design
  decision, made to keep the program simple. If I was to start over today I
  might do things differently, but it's too much effort to change now. In
  typical usage this should not be a problem.

- WeatherStation doesn't support localization- in particular, it only
  supports English as a language. When I started work on WeatherStation, I
  did not have access to information on the workings of the locale.library.
  Further, with the ID-5001 mainly (if not exclusively) available in the
  US, and with the suspected very small potential user base for
  WeatherStation, it seemed unlikely that it would ever be translated into
  another language. So I simplified things by leaving this feature out.

- WeatherStation is not very colorful, running with only four colors
  regardless of the available screen depth. This was done for simplicity.
  All Amiga video modes support at least four colors, so WeatherStation can
  open on any screen without worrying about how many colors are available.

- WeatherStation doesn't support keyboard shortcuts for its control buttons
  (this is the program's main area of style guide non-compliance). I
  started to support this, but the large number of buttons on some windows
  meant that I'd be struggling to find shortcuts that were even remotely
  mnemonic. When I got to the "clear" buttons in the High/Low window I gave
  up completely.

- WeatherStation doesn't allow use of the standard Amiga ASL requesters.
  This is because only the ReqTools requesters have a fully-asynchronous
  mode that allows WeatherStation to keep monitoring the serial port and
  displaying and recording data even while a requester is open.

- The "select file" buttons don't scale when adapting to different font
  sizes, so they tend to look funny with fonts that aren't 8 pixels high.
  This is a limitation in the custom button code provided with GadToolsBox.

- WeatherStation doesn't use double-buffering when playing IFF sounds, so
  it can't play a sound longer than 128K samples (per channel). This
  simplified the code, and 128K samples seemed like enough for a simple
  annunciator.

- Chart recorder windows are always refreshed whenever they are touching
  the screen title bar and a menu selection is made. This is true even if
  the menu selection has changed a chart parameter, which will itself cause
  a chart redraw. As a result, the chart redraws twice, once with the old
  parameters, then again with the new. With a large chart window and a slow
  Amiga, this is annoying. This is a byproduct of Intuition, which sends a
  window refresh message before sending the new menu selection, even though
  the method it uses for rendering menus insures that no refresh is
  necessary. MagicMenu doesn't do this, and so does not exhibit this
  problem.

- This may or may not be a shortcoming, depending on your point of view:
  WeatherStation uses simple refresh windows. This significantly reduces
  the amount of chip RAM required, but also makes refresh of the windows
  slower. Since WeatherStation can potentially open a lot of windows, I
  felt that reducing RAM usage was more important than having the fastest
  possible window refresh.

- WeatherStation is very fussy about file formats. Even a minor formatting
  error in a data file will cause the file to be rejected. This ensures
  that corrupted data will not be loaded, but it might be better to be
  a little more lenient.

- WeatherStation's ARexx port is pretty basic. It would be nice if it
  allowed more control over the operation of the program.

@{u}ID-5001 Bugs and Shortcomings@{uu}

- WeatherStation is year 2000 compliant, as is the Amiga OS. The ID-5001
  has a minor year 2000 bug, however. When the year, as read via the
  serial port, increments from 99 it becomes 100 instead of 00. Weather-
  Station rejects a three-digit year as being improperly formatted,
  causing the date and time in the Display window to go blank.

  The bug does not otherwise affect operation of the ID-5001, and so may
  persist for some time after the century rollover. If WeatherStation
  refuses to display the time and date from the ID-5001, this is probably
  the problem. To correct this error, just re-enter the time and date from
  the ID-5001's front panel, using 00 for the year.

- Later model ID-5001s can calculate and display the outdoor dewpoint.
  As far as I've been able to determine, this data is not available via the
  serial port, leaving WeatherStation with no way to display it.

@endnode

@node "ARexx" "ARexx Port"

@{b}@{fg shine}ARexx Port@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}----------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation features an ARexx port that allows ARexx or ARexx-compatible
applications to communicate with it. The port is currently rather limited,
but it is sufficient to allow other programs access to the current weather
readings, which provides a basis for more sophisticated operations on the
data than WeatherStation itself can provide. The port also allows external
programs basic control over the charting and data recording features of
WeatherStation.

WeatherStation's ARexx port has the name WEATHERSTATION. If more than one
copy of WeatherStation is running, the second copy's port will be named
WEATHERSTATION.1, and additional copies will get successively higher
numbers.

WeatherStation returns the value 0 in the ARexx variable RC if the ARexx
command was successful. It returns the value 10 if the command failed, and
the value 20 if the command was not recognized, or if the ARexx port is
not active (i.e., WeatherStation is shutting down).

WeatherStation supports the following ARexx commands:

@{"CHART" link "ARexxChart" 0}
@{"GET_READINGS" link "ARexxGetReadings" 0}
@{"RECORD" link "ARexxRecord" 0}

To demonstrate WeatherStation's ARexx port, some example ARexx scripts
are provided:

@{"Example.rexx" link "Example.rexx/MAIN"} provides a basic example of how to access WeatherStation's
ARexx port, and provides a simple example of each of the supported
commands.

@{"WebWeather.rexx" link "WebWeather.rexx/MAIN"} demonstrates how to use WeatherStation data to create an
HTML page containing the current weather readings. While functional, this
example is more of a "proof-of-concept" than a polished application.

@{"DoWebWeather.rexx" link "DoWebWeather.rexx/MAIN"} calls WebWeather.rexx on a regular basis, causing the
HTML weather page to be updated continuously. Again, this is more of a
"proof-of-concept" than a polished application.

@endnode

@node "ARexxChart" "ARexx CHART Command"
@toc "ARexx"

@{b}CHART Filename [Filename] [Filename] [Filename] [Realtime]@{ub}

This command attempts to load the named file as a @{"WXD data file" link "WXD File Format" 0}, and open a
@{"chart recorder window" link "Chart" 0} to display it. More than one file name may be given
(up to four), causing more than one chart recorder window to be opened. If
more names are specified than there are windows available, the additional
names are ignored. The @{"Chart Control window" link "Chart Ctrl" 0} is opened, if not already open.

The file name "Realtime" (not case sensitive) is treated specially- it
causes the realtime chart recorder window to be opened, rather than loading
a file. Because the realtime chart does not use one of the four filename
'slots' in the Chart Control window, it may be specified in addition to the
four filenames. If the realtime chart is already open, the "Realtime" name
will be ignored.

A return code of zero indicates that WeatherStation was able to add each of
the specified files to the Chart Control window as files to be charted. It
does not indicate that the program was actually able to load and display
all (or any) of the files. Conversely, a return code of 10 means that the
Chart Control window did not have slots for all of the given files. Some
or all of the files it did have slots for may have been loaded.

The main use for the return code, then, is to know when WeatherStation has
all of its chart recorder windows open already, and it's necessary to run
another copy of the program in order to open the file in question.

Note that the Chart Control window considers a file to be loaded if its
name is present in the Chart File Name text gadget, even if the chart
recorder window itself is not open. If you've finished looking at a file
and want to open up slots for additional files to be loaded, delete the
file name from the gadget.

@endnode

@node "ARexxGetReadings" "ARexx GET_READINGS Command"
@toc "ARexx"

@{b}GET_READINGS [UNITS WBTR] [VAR VarName] [STEM StemName.]@{ub}

This command returns the current weather readings, as read from the
ID-5001. For maximum flexibility, the readings may be returned in the
standard ARexx RESULT variable, or they may be returned in a specified
variable or compound variable.

The argument UNITS, if present, is followed by four letters that indicate
which units of measurement to use in returning the readings, These need not
be the same as the units that WeatherStation or the ID-5001 are displaying.
If UNITS is not specified, the units being displayed by the ID-5001 will be
used.

The first letter specifies the windspeed units. It is either 'M' or 'm' for
MPH, 'L' or 'l' for KPH, or 'K' or 'k' for knots. The second letter
specifies the barometer units. It is either 'I' or 'i' for inches, or 'M'
or 'm' for millibars. The third letter specifies the temperature units. It
is either 'F' or 'f' for Fahrenheit, or 'C' or 'c' for Celsius. The final
letter specifies the rainfall units. It is either 'I' or 'i' for inches, or
'C' or 'c' for centimeters.

The VAR argument, if present, specifies the name of the variable in which
the readings are to be returned. If VAR is not specified, the standard
ARexx variable RESULT is used.

The STEM argument, if present, specifies a compound variable in which the
readings are to be returned (note the period after the variable's name).
The STEM argument may be present in addition to the VAR argument, in which
case the readings will be returned in both variables.

If returned in a standard variable (RESULT or one specified via the VAR
argument), the readings are returned as a string with the following format
(all on one line):

 RESULT or VarName = NNNN w DD MM YY HH MM W B T R AAA DDD GGG DDD BBBB
 [-]ttt [-]TTT [-]ccc [-]CCCC hh HH RRRR

If returned in a compound variable, the readings are returned as a series
of substrings making up the compound variable:

 StemName.SERIAL = NNNN
 StemName.DATE = w DD MM YY
 StemName.TIME = HH MM
 StemName.UNITS = W B T R
 StemName.WINDAVG = AAA DDD
 StemName.WINDGUST = GGG DDD
 StemName.BAROM = BBBB
 StemName.INTEMP = [-]ttt
 StemName.OUTTEMP = [-]TTT
 StemName.AVGCHILL = [-]ccc
 StemName.GUSTCHILL = [-]CCCC
 StemName.INHUMID = hh
 StemName.OUTHUMID = HH
 StemName.RAIN = RRRR

For ease of parsing by ARexx or by other programs, values are separated by
spaces, and have no decimal points or other punctuation (except a minus
sign for negative numbers). Numbers will not have more digits than
indicated (except as noted in the next paragraph), but may have fewer.

If any reading is not available (because the corresponding sensor is not
connected, because WeatherStation is not connected to an ID-5001, or
because of some other error) the value of that reading will be -128 (except
for the units flags, which will be set to default values).

NNNN is a serial number that is incremented every time a new set of
readings becomes available (wrapping back to zero after 9999). It may be
used to tell when new readings are available, since this may not be
apparent from examination of the other values. The rate at which new
readings become available is dependent on the rate at which WeatherStation
reads them from the ID-5001, as controlled by the @{"Preferences" link "SerialPrefs" 0} settings.

w is the day of the week (0 = Monday, and 6 = Sunday), DD is the date
(1 - 31), MM is the month (1 - 12), and YY is the year (0 - 99) when the
reading was made.

HH is the hour (0 - 23), and MM is the minute (0 - 59) when the reading was
made.

W is the wind units (M for MPH, L for KPH, or K for knots); B is the
barometer units (I for inches, M for millibars); T is the temperature
(including wind chill) units (F for Fahrenheit, C for Celsius); R is the
rainfall units (I for inches, C for centimeters).

AAA is the average windspeed, in MPH, KPH, or knots; DDD is the average
wind direction, in degrees (0 - 359).

GGG is the gust windspeed, in MPH, KPH, or knots; DDD is the gust wind
direction, in degrees (0 - 359).

BBBB is the barometer, in inches * 100 (i.e., 3015 = 30.15) or in
millibars.

ttt is the indoor temperature, in Fahrenheit or Celsius. A minus sign is
prepended if the temperature is negative.

TTT is the outdoor temperature, in Fahrenheit or Celsius. A minus sign is
prepended if the temperature is negative.

ccc is the average wind chill temperature, in Fahrenheit or Celsius. A
minus sign is prepended if the temperature is negative.

ccc is the gust wind chill temperature, in Fahrenheit or Celsius. A minus
sign is prepended if the temperature is negative.

hh is the indoor humidity, in percent.

HH is the outdoor humidity, in percent.

RRRR is the rainfall, in inches * 100 (i.e., 105 = 1.05) or in centimeters
* 100 (i.e., 110 = 1.10).

@endnode

@node "ARexxRecord" "ARexx RECORD Command"
@toc "ARexx"

@{b}RECORD Filename | Stop@{ub}

This command attempts to begin recording of weather data to the named @{"WXD" link "WXD File Format" 0}
@{"data file" link "WXD File Format" 0}, using the parameters currently set in the @{"Record Control window" link "Record Ctrl" 0}
(which will be opened, if not already open).

If the named file aleady exists and is a WXD file, it will be appended to.
If it is not a WXD file, recording will be aborted. If recording is already
in progress, the command will be ignored (but will generate a return code
of 10). In all of these cases no requesters will appear to inform the user
what is going on, as ARexx operation is intended to be automated.

This command returns before WeatherStation actually tries to write to the
named file. Because of this, the command may return a result of zero, even
though it is not possible to write to the data file. An error in writing to
the file will generate a requester.

The filename "Stop" (not case sensitive) is treated specially- it causes
recording to be terminated. If recording is not underway, the "Stop"
filename will be ignored.

@endnode

@node "Example" "Example.wxd"

@{b}@{fg shine}Example.wxd@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}-----------@{ub}@{fg text}

Included with WeatherStation is @{"Example.wxd" link "Example.wxd/main" 0}, an example WeatherStation
data file that may be used to explore the chart recorder interface, even if
you don't have access to an ID-5001.

Example.wxd was actually recorded by a program running on my Radio Shack
Model 100. I tend to use the M100 to record data, rather than the Amiga,
because the M100 is completely silent, uses very little power, and runs
unscathed through power outages. The WXD file format was designed to allow
weather data files to be recorded by other systems, and this is an example
of that use.

The disadvantage of using the M100 is that it has only enough RAM to hold
24 hours worth of data, at a five minute recording interval. So every night
at midnight, I unplug the M100 from the ID-5001, and download its data into
the Amiga. If you look closely, you'll see brief gaps in the recorded data
while this occurs. So Example.wxd is really eight separate data files, all
concatenated together. The WXD file format was designed to allow this, as
well.

The outdoor humidity sensor on my ID-5001 is broken, so there is no outdoor
humidity information recorded. Also, the Model 100 program does not have a
"record maximums" setting for the wind speed, so the wind speeds recorded
are those present at the moment of the recording.

To view a chart of the Example.wxd data file, open the @{"Chart Control" link "Chart Ctrl" 0}
@{"window" link "Chart Ctrl" 0}, then press the Chart Source button until File #1 is selected. Use
the file requester to select Example.wxd. This will cause the file to be
scanned. You'll see that all of the readings except the outdoor humidity
are selected for charting. Press the Chart button, and the data file will
be read into memory, and a chart recorder window will be opened.

Alternately, you can double-click on the Example.wxd icon, and the file
will be loaded and a chart recorder window opened to display it.

You'll probably want to enlarge the @{"chart recorder window" link "Chart" 0}, in order to
better see the charts. You can play with the horizontal and vertical
scaling as you wish. You'll notice event markers at the beginning of each
day's data. Double click the event marker to read the corresponding file
note. These notes explain the data, and point out some interesting
observations.

When done looking at the chart, click its close gadget, or press the Close
button in the Chart Control window.

If you're interested in the @{"WXD file format" link "WXD File Format" 0}, you can use any text viewer
to look at Example.wxd and see how the data is presented.

@endnode

@node "WXD File Format" "WXD File Format"

@{b}@{fg shine}WXD File Format@{ub}@{fg text}
@{b}@{fg shine}---------------@{ub}@{fg text}

WeatherStation uses a file format known as WXD (Weather Data) for storing
recorded weather readings. The WXD format was designed for versatility. The
goal is to make WXD files easy to create on other platforms as well as the
Amiga, to make it easy to edit the files using only a basic text editor or
word processor, and to make it relatively easy to convert the files to
other formats, such as for import into a spreadsheet or database. The
tradeoff for this versatility is that the format is relatively inefficient,
with lengthy recordings becoming rather large.

The WXD file format uses plain ASCII text. Except for file notes, which may
contain special (i.e., foreign language) characters, only standard 7-bit
ASCII is used. WXD files consist of a series of lines, each roughly 80
characters or less, and each terminated by either a carriage return (<CR>),
a line feed (<LF>), or a carriage return and a line feed (<CR><LF>). Each
line is a record, and each record is identified as to its type by the first
character in the line.

WXD format data files are organized as follows:

o The first line in the file is a @{"file header record" link "File Header Recd" 0}, identifying the file
  type.

o Next is an optional @{"comment record" link "Comment Recd" 0}, indicating what program made the
  recording.

o Next is another optional @{"comment record" link "Comment Recd" 0}, identifying the fields of the
  following data header record (for human readability).

o Following is a @{"data header record" link "Data Header Recd" 0}, identifying the start date and time
  of the data recording, the recording interval, and the units being used.

o Next is an optional @{"comment record" link "Comment Recd" 0}, identifying the fields of the
  following data records (for human readability).

o Following is a series of @{"data records" link "Data Recd" 0}, recorded every specified
  recording interval. The time of the recording is not kept. Instead, when
  reading a WXD file the reader program must keep track of the date and
  time of each data record.

o @{"Note records" link "Note Recd" 0} may optionally be interspersed with the data records,
  commenting on what is being recorded.

o @{"Other record types" link "Other Recd" 0} may be defined in the future. Older file readers will
  safely ignore these new records.

o There is no special "end of file" record. The file ends when there are no
  more lines.

Because WXD files are simple ASCII text files, they may readily be created
on other platforms, and transported to the Amiga via any means of
transferring ASCII text. The format is forgiving of the different "end of
line" formats used by different platforms.

An ordinary text editor or word processor may be used to edit WXD files (be
sure to save word-processed files as plain ASCII text, not the native
format of the word processor). One reason to do this would be to add
comments to a recording after the fact.

@endnode

@node "File Header Recd" "WXD File Header Record"
@toc "WXD File Format"

File header record: first character = ';'

A WXD file must start with a file header record. This record serves to
identify the file, both to a program that wants to interpret it, and to a
human who wants to know "what's in that file?"

The file version number allows for future changes to the file format,
enabling new file readers to recognize an older format and convert it, and
older readers to report that they don't know how to read a newer format.

The header record is a @{"comment record" link "Comment Recd" 0} that reads as follows:

;WeatherStation Data File, v 1.0<EOL>

@endnode

@node "Comment Recd" "WXD Comment Record"
@toc "WXD File Format"

Comment record: first character = ';'

Records that start with the comment identifier are ignored by file readers.
Comments are intended mainly to make the file easier to read by humans; for
instance, indentifying the fields in the data records.

Comment records should be limited to 80 characters or less. They may use
extended ASCII characters, though doing so will reduce portability.

An example:

;This is a hidden comment.<EOL>

@endnode

@node "Note Recd" "WXD Note Record"
@toc "WXD File Format"

Note record: first character = '*'

Records that start with the note identifier serve as notes, typically
containing commentary on the nearby data records. Notes are available to be
displayed by the reader program. Notes may contain extended ASCII
characters, though doing so will reduce portability. The * character may
appear within a note record.

Note records should be limited to 80 characters or less, and lengths of 40
characters or less will be easiest to display. A series of adjacent note
records will be considered a single note. An empty note (* followed by
<EOL>) will equate to a blank line.

An example:

*This is the first line of a note.<EOL>
*<EOL>
*This is the third line of the same note.<EOL>

@endnode

@node "Data Header Recd" "WXD Data Header Recd"
@toc "WXD File Format"

Data header record: first character = '#'

A data header record contains information about the data records that
follow it. The data header record must appear before any data records, as
it defines how those records will be interpreted.

A data header record takes the following form:

# WWW, DD-MMM-YY, HH:MM[:SS], RR, W, B, T, R<EOL>

The fields are defined as shown below. The field separators are commas.
Spaces may be inserted for readability; they will be ignored by file
readers. Numeric values may have leading zeroes or may have fewer digits
than indicated, but will not have more.

- WWW is the day of the week of the first data record, in three-letter
  abbreviation format (i.e., Sun = Sunday).

- DD-MMM-YY is the date of the first data record, in standard Amiga date
  format (i.e., 29-May-94).

- HH:MM is the time of the first data record, in 24 hour format. Seconds
  are optional.

- RR is the recording interval, in minutes.

- W is the wind speed units, either K for knots, L for KPH, or M for MPH.
  B is the barometer units, either I for inches or M for millibars.
  T is the temperature units, either C for Celsius, or F for Fahrenheit.
  R is the rainfall units, either C for cm or I for inches.
  (Either upper or lower case letters are acceptable; upper case is
  preferred.)

An example:

# Mon, 02-Feb-98, 00:40:00, 5, M, I, F, I<EOL>

@endnode

@node "Data Recd" "WXD Data Record"
@toc "WXD File Format"

Any line whose first non-space character is a comma or a numeral (0 - 9) is
considered a data record.

A data record contains data read from the weather computer at a single
point in time. The first data record following a data header record is
assumed to have been recorded at the time indicated in the header record.
Each succeeding data record is assumed to have been recorded after the time
interval specified in the header record.

A data record takes the following form:

AAA, DDD, GGG, DDD, BBBB, [-]ttt, [-]TTT, [-]CCC, hh, HH, RRRR<EOL>

The fields are defined as shown below. The field separators are commas.
Spaces may be inserted for readability; they will be ignored by file
readers. Numeric values may have leading zeroes or may have fewer digits
than indicated, but will not have more.

If a particular field is not being recorded, the field is left empty (i.e.,
only a comma (and optional space) is present).

- AAA, DDD is the average wind speed, in the units specified in the data
  header, and the direction, in degrees.

- GGG, DDD is the instantaneous (gust) wind speed, in the units specified
  in the data header, and the direction, in degrees.

- BBBB is the barometer reading, in the units specified in the data header.
  Inches are in hundredths, i.e., 2995 = 29.95.

- [-]ttt is the indoor temperature, in the units specified in the data
  header. A minus sign will precede the number when it is negative.

- [-]TTT is the outdoor temperature, in the units specified in the data
  header. A minus sign will precede the number when it is negative.

- [-]CCC is the wind chill temperature per the instantaneous (gust) wind
  speed, in the units specified in the data header. A minus sign will
  preceed the number when it is negative.

- hh is the indoor humidity, in percent.

- HH is the outdoor humidity, in percent.

- RRRR is the delta rainfall, in the units specified in the data header.
  Delta rainfall means that the difference between the previous absolute
  reading and the current absolute reading is recorded (i.e., if the
  previous reading was 1.61 and the current reading is 1.66, then the
  value recorded is 5). Readings are in hundredths, for both units
  (i.e., 101 = 1.01" or 1.01 cm).

An example:

13, 180, 11, 210, 2925, 71, 56, 46, 61, , 11<EOL>

@endnode

@node "Other Recd" "Other WXD Records"
@toc "WXD File Format"

Any line whose first non-space character is not one otherwise defined will
be ignored by version 1.0 WXD file readers. This will allow for more record
types to be created in the future, while remaining compatible with older
readers.

An empty line, consisting of only an <EOL>, will also be ignored by file
readers.

@endnode

